I've noticed that the driver does not mind if {{maxPoolSize}} gets set to a value lesser than {{minPoolSize}}:
{code}
static String uri = "mongodb://adminx:123@mubuntu:27017/test?authSource=admin&minPoolSize=1000&maxPoolSize=10";
{code}

I believe that the behaviour in such a configuration is undefined.

For comparison, the Java driver throws if the same connection string is used (which I believe is the correct behaviour):
{noformat}
java.lang.IllegalStateException: state should be: maxSize >= minSize
{noformat}

The NativeMethods.CreateException method maps a known errorCode to a corresponding string, but if the errorCode is not one we know about we use the defaultMessage.

When the defaultMessage is used this way some information is lost because we don't know what the errorCode was.

We should append the error code to the default message, something like:
{code:java}
 message = defaultMessage + $" Error code {errorCode}.";
{code}

The following should result in an exception thrown when RegisterSerializer is called:

{code}
var intSerializer = new Int32Serializer();
BsonSerializer.RegisterSerializer(typeof(long), intSerializer);
{code}

because the types don't agree.

Simple repro:

{code:java}
var filter = Builders<ClassWithBsonTypes>.Filter.Eq(o => o.BsonDocument.ElementCount, 1);
filter.Render(new(BsonSerializer.SerializerRegistry.GetSerializer<ClassWithBsonTypes>(), BsonSerializer.SerializerRegistry));

public class ClassWithBsonTypes
{
    public BsonDocument BsonDocument { get; set; }
}
{code}

fails with:
System.ArgumentException: Serializer value type MongoDB.Bson.BsonValue is incompatible with expression value type System.Int32 (Parameter 'serializer')

